          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>The Mixo route:</strong> Launched landing page in 20 minutes. Clean, professional. Started getting traffic. Month 3, wanted to add customer case studies section. Mixo CMS was basic - couldn't handle the content structure he needed. Spent 12 hours hacking workarounds with custom HTML blocks. Month 6, wanted to add user dashboard feature. Mixo can't do it - no code export, no API access. Stuck.</p>

          <div class="bg-sky-100 border-l-[4px] border-sky-500 p-4 my-4">
            <p class="text-sm text-sky-900 font-medium"><strong>The breaking point:</strong> Month 8, landed enterprise client who needed custom portal. Webflow version: Export code, add custom React components, deploy to Vercel. Mixo version: Impossible - locked into platform. Had to rebuild entire site from scratch.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-blue-100 border-l-[4px] border-blue-500 p-4 my-4">
            <p class="text-sm text-blue-900 font-medium"><strong>The brutal math:</strong> 8 months on Mixo = $72 total cost. But 40 hours wasted on CMS workarounds + 80 hours rebuilding site when scaling. At founder's $200/hour opportunity cost, that's $24,000 in lost time. The "$6/month savings" cost $24,000.</p>
          </div>

          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>The lesson:</strong> Mixo is perfect when you know your needs won't change. Simple portfolio, basic blog, landing page that stays static - Mixo is unbeatable value. But if you're building something that might scale, need custom features, or want flexibility to export code later, pay the extra $6/month for Webflow.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
